node.text:
Some of my go-tos! Enjoy 😊 

Greek Inspired Salad Jar
* 1-2 cups kale
* 1 tbsp feta cheese
* 4oz chicken thighs 
* 10 olives 
* ¼ cup red onion 
* ½ orange bell pepper 
* ½ cup chickpeas
* 1 tbsp balsamic

BLT Remix Salad jar 
* 1 cup mixed greens
* 2 pieces nitrate free bacon
* 2 eggs 
* ½ cup cucumber 
* 1 cup tomatoes 
* 2 tbsp paleo ranch

Veggie Goddess
* 1 cup mixed greens
* ½ cup red onion 
* ½ cup black beans 
* ½ cup quinoa
* ½ cup cucumber 
* ½ cup tomatoes 
* 1 tbsp balsamic

Tex Mex Jar Combo 
* 1 tbsp cilantro 
* 2 cup lettuce   
* 4oz ground turkey or grass-fed ground beef
* ½ cup corn
* ¼ cup onion 
* ½ cup bell peppers 
* ½ cup tomatoes 
* 1 tbsp balsamic

Tofu vs egg scramble - which do you prefer? 😁

Made this fun collab video with @yovana. Because it’s great to show how you can tweak a recipe to your mood or dietary prefer. Both are great IMO. Full recipe below: 💛TOFU SCRAMBLE
1/2 block Tofu 
1/2 tbs Avocado oil 
1/4 cup Onion
1  Tomato
1/2 Jalapeño
1/4 tsp Cumin
1/2 tsp Turmeric 
1/4 tsp Black Pepper
1/4 tsp Garlic powder
1/2 tsp Sea salt 
Small bunch Cilantro
1/4 Avocado 🥚SCRAMBLED EGGS
2-3 Eggs
1 tbs Butter 
1/4 tsp Onion
1 Tomato
1/4 tsp Cumin
1/2 tsp Turmeric 1/4 tsp Black Pepper
1/4 tsp Garlic powder
1/2 tsp Sea salt 
Small bunch Cilantro
1/4 Avocado 
#recipe #mealprep #breakfast

node.text:
Coconut oil pulling benefits:
Fights bad breath,
improves gum health &
maintains teeth whitness.

What to do:
Step 1: Swish 1 tbsp coconut oil in your mouth for 10-15 min (yes min!) Step 2: Spit in trash afterwards since oil will clog the drains
Step 3: Brush your teeth normally after and floss like you normally would.

Cheers to great oral health!
Xoxo
Amanda

Here’s to building a well rounded routine 🏋️‍♀️ ⁠
⁠
Part of the reason I emphasize strength training so much is because I used to be an absolute cardio addict. While I still incorporate cardio a lot into my routine, I’ve noticed how much better I feel overall by making some form of strength training a priority in my weekly routine.⁠
⁠
Whether you’re using strength training to compliment a running routine or cardio to compliment a strength program, it’s crucial to support your body in a variety of ways.⁠
⁠
Another thing I do notice is people tend to overdo cardio when their goal is fat loss. That’s another reason I emphasize weights and that you definitely don’t want to overtrain nor do you need a ton of cardio to hit your fat loss goals. Overtraining or doing an insane amount of cardio could definitely result in an injury or feeling run down and I want to make sure you’re feeling good and your body is well supported.⁠
⁠
Lastly, I personally notice that I feel better when incorporating yoga once a week. Mobility, yoga or stretching can definitely also help to prevent injury and support healthy movement in other parts of your routine.⁠
⁠

Make time for you ❤️ Because you deserve to feel your best.⁠⁠
—⁠⁠
The default state of any organism is health. And it doesn’t come from some fringe diet. It doesn’t come from a cross-fit regimen. It doesn’t come from a supplement. And it doesn’t come counting calories. These are all tools and should be used as such but the primary variable is you. What are you doing every day to create habits that will lead you to your best, most optimal self? It doesn’t have to be all or nothing—as long as you’re progressing daily (and this could be in terms of your diet, the scale, your lifts, your sleep quality, or even your mindset) you’re on the right path.⁣⁣⁠⁠
⁣⁠⁠
Also, this shouldn’t be taken to imply that by doing everything “right” (i.e. some illusory notion of perfection) that illness is completely avoidable. Definitely not so. Genes and, to be honest, luck also play a part and for that we have modern medicine. But when it comes to lifestyle conditions, by far the most common ailments affecting humans today, the research is clear: we do have a say.⁣⁠⁠
—⁠⁠

What’s your drink of choice? ☕️ 🍵 ⁠
⁠
Whether you’re a matcha lover or coffee addict, it’s great to get a gauge of where your caffeine level is landing. While there’s no guide to where you should exactly land, if you notice yourself feeling extra jittery, anxious or cracked out, that may be a sign you’re overdoing it in the caffeine arena. The amount can also vary wildly per brand so make sure to check in with yourself & how you’re feeling. ⁠
⁠
For people more sensitive to caffeine, matcha and green tea can often be a great choice not just because of the often lower caffeine levels but the L-Theanine found in these drinks that can help to balance out the jittery feeling often associated with caffeine while still helping to improve focus & energy. ⁠
⁠
Lastly, herbal teas are a great way to enjoy a delightlful drink without adding extra caffeine to your day.⁠
⁠
Reminder that caffeine levels will vary by amount and brand so double check with your local coffee shop or brand sourced if you’re looking for the exact amount of caffeine in your drink.⁠
⁠
*Average amounts listed for: 12oz nitro, 12oz cold brew, 12oz coffee, 1 espresso shot, 1 teaspoon of matcha mixed w/ 12oz hot water, 1 bag black tea, 1 bag green tea, 1 bag herbal tea*⁠

Sugar is hidden in more foods than many are aware of!⁠
⁠
That’s why it’s more important now than ever to become an informed consumer. It’s up to you to take matters of your health into your own hands.⁠
⁠
The book @sugarproofkids by Michael L. Goran, PhD is a great deep dive into all things sugar and what you can do about it.⁠
⁠
One key takeaway is that while a lot of sugars are similar, fructose is a the type of sugar you’ll want to minimize overall when it’s not paired with the appropriate fiber.⁠
⁠
Fructose found in fruit is encapsulated in a fiber-rich flesh which helps to slow the absorption down, making it a lighter load on your liver.⁠
⁠
High fructose corn syrup, agave nectar and fruit juice concentrates are all examples of sweeteners with a higher concentration of fructose that you’d want to minimize overall.⁠
⁠
Remember that the most important thing is paying attention to your total sugar load for the day and when you can opt for whole fruit over added sugars 😘⁠
⁠

While everyone is headed back to school we can’t forget about our college students!⁠⁠

Love this post by @just.ingredients , she shares great swaps! More below:⁠⁠

Not surprisingly, their immune systems can take a hit, due to some college kids lifestyles. So here are some tips to help keep college age kids healthy this year!⁠⁠

1️⃣Sleep-⁠⁠
It’s often not a priority-those late nights and early classes can take a toll!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
During sleep, the brain not only consolidates learning and memory but also strengthens immune memory. Sleep “reinforces the immune systems ability to remember how to recognize and react to dangerous antigens. Getting enough high quality sleep facilitates the delicate balance of immune function.”1⁠⁠

Tips on How to Fix Bloating + Tips To Support A Healthy Gut⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Causes of bloating can be complex and not fun for those who experience it frequently. I wanted to share some tips with you on what could be triggering bloating and ways to fix it. Now, this isn’t a one-size-fits all approach. These are some tips that have helped me and I hope they can help you too.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Additionally, the gut is one of the most important organs in your body that directly affects how you feel, & many other aspects of overall health. That’s why it’s crucial to support a healthy gut with proper nutrition & a healthy lifestyle.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 1: Eat mindfully and slowly - Ensuring adequate chewing of your food can have two benefits - reducing the amount of air you swallow (which can cause bloating) & eating slower gives your body more time to signal feelings of fullness.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 2: Limit sugar alcohols - sugar alcohols in high amounts can also lead to bloating.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 3: Watch your fiber intake - Eating too much or too little fiber can also cause bloating, so find a happy medium!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 4: Mix in fermented foods or a probiotic - probiotics found in fermented foods or a supplement can help improve the bacterial environment in the gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 5: Drink lemon ginger or peppermint tea - Both ginger & peppermint have been shown to sooth & aid w/ digestion.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 6: Check for underlying food sensitives/allergies.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 7:  Drink lots of water: Proper hydration has been shown to have a beneficial effect on the balance of good bacteria in the gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 8: Prioritize sleep: Quality of sleep can have serious impacts on your gut health.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 9: Limit processed Foods: A diet high in ultra processed foods and added sugars can cause an imbalance of good bacteria in your gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 10: Eat prebiotic: fibers are foods that promote the growth of beneficial microbes in your gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tip 11: Manage street levels: Chronic high levels of stress can have an array of negative affects including a negative impact on your gut.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
